$BODY = <<<'HTML'
<p>When a sound follows you everywhere and steals your sleep, mood pays the price. Feeling down, irritable or empty with severe tinnitus is not a character weakness: it is an understandable reaction. And it is also reversible.</p>

<h2>A real connection, in two directions</h2>
<p>Tinnitus and mood influence each other. The ringing disrupts sleep and concentration, which lowers mood; in turn, a low psychological state makes the brain more sensitive to the sound. Among people with severe tinnitus, <span class="num">48–60%</span> report anxiety or depression. Recognising the cycle is the first step to breaking it.</p>

<h2>What has the strongest evidence: CBT</h2>
<p>Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) reduces tinnitus-related distress by <span class="num">10.91</span> points on the THI scale (Cochrane review of 28 studies, 2,733 patients). It does not reduce the loudness of the ringing: it changes the relationship with it, reducing anxiety and depressive mood. It is the intervention with the best evidence, without serious side effects.</p>

<h2>And medication?</h2>
<p>Antidepressants do not treat tinnitus itself: Cochrane reviews support them only when there is clinical depression or anxiety to address. AAO-HNS guidelines do not recommend routine medications and supplements for the ringing. The right direction is psychological and behavioural, not a pill against the sound.</p>

<h2>When to seek help immediately</h2>
<p>If thoughts appear that you cannot cope any longer, that you might harm yourself, or that days are losing their meaning, do not wait: talk to a doctor immediately or contact an emergency service. Severe distress from tinnitus can be treated, and no one needs to face it alone.</p>

<h2>In short</h2>
<p>Low mood with tinnitus is common and understandable — and it improves. CBT, consistent sleep and support from those around you make the difference; medication is useful only if there is depression to treat. And in the face of the darkest thoughts, help must be sought immediately.</p>
